-- Bradespar, Inepar, MMX, Petrobras, Telmex: Latin America Equity Preview
-- Alexander Ragir
-- 2010-07-26T03:00:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-26/bradespar-inepar-mmx-petrobras-telmex-latin-america-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
unusual price changes in Latin American trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses and share prices reflect the previous close.  
 The  MSCI Latin America Index  rose 0.5 percent to 4,023.21
on July 23. In Brazil, preferred shares usually are the most-
traded class of stock.  
 Brazil  
 Bradespar SA  (BRAP4 BS): The holding unit of Banco Bradesco
SA said on July 23 its board approved a buyback of as many as
1.5 million shares within six months. The board authorized
Bradespar to buy as many as 500,000 common shares and 1 million
preferred shares, the company said. The stock rose 2.5 percent
to 36.40 reais.  
 Inepar SA Industria e Construcoes  (INEP4 BS): The electric
power equiptment manufacturer is issuing 29.9 million shares in
a private offering to boost capital by 140 million reais,
according to a regulatory filing on July 23. The stock gained
6.5 percent to 5.22 reais.  
 MMX Mineracao e Metalicos SA  (MMXM3 BS): The iron ore
company controlled by billionaire Eike Batista is in talks with
ArcelorMittal to form a partnership to help supply iron ore,
Veja magazine reported on July 24 in its Holofote column. MMX
rose 2 percent to 11.87 reais.  
 Petroleo Brasileiro SA  (PETR4 BS): Petrobras plans to begin
oil production at its Tupi field in the Campos Basin by
September, three months earlier than previously forecast, O
Globo newspaper reported on July 24, citing an unidentified aide
to President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva. The stock fell 0.7
percent to 27.79 reais.  
 Mexico  
 Telmex Internacional SAB  (TELINTL MM), The South American
phone company controlled by America Movil SAB said second-
quarter profit fell 43 percent on foreign-exchange losses,
according to a regulatory filing late July 23. The stock fell
0.3 percent to 11.62 pesos.  
